comment_data.body:
> Hello, I was experimenting again with setting CYTHON_LIMITED_API define macro. Is it expected and normal that, e.g. if I build the *.abi3.so with python3.8 and then try to import it from python3.9 I get a warning that the compiletime version does not much the runtime version?
> 
> ```
> RuntimeWarning: compiletime version 3.8 of module 'cu2qu.cu2qu' does not match runtime version 3.9
> ```

I just found myself in the same situation. I think this warning may confuse users compiling with `CYTHON_LIMITED_API`. Somebody using this feature actually wants to compile with one unique Python 3.x and be able to run with multiple Python >= 3.x. There are already other functions being preprocessed based on `CYTHON_COMPILING_IN_LIMITED_API`, and `__Pyx_check_binary_version` seems to need it too:
https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/ddaaa7b8bfe9885b7bed432cd0a5ab8191d112cd/Cython/Utility/ModuleSetupCode.c#L1550-L1563

One possibility would be to skip the `RuntimeError` in the case of the limited API:
```python
static int __Pyx_check_binary_version(void) {
    #if !CYTHON_COMPILING_IN_LIMITED_API
    char ctversion[4], rtversion[4];
    PyOS_snprintf(ctversion, 4, "%d.%d", PY_MAJOR_VERSION, PY_MINOR_VERSION);
    PyOS_snprintf(rtversion, 4, "%s", Py_GetVersion());
    if (ctversion[0] != rtversion[0] || ctversion[2] != rtversion[2]) {
        char message[200];
        PyOS_snprintf(message, sizeof(message),
                      "compile time version %s of module '%.100s' "
                      "does not match runtime version %s",
                      ctversion, __Pyx_MODULE_NAME, rtversion);
        return PyErr_WarnEx(NULL, message, 1);
    }
    #endif
    return 0;
}
```
Another possibility would be to restrict the version check in the limited API case so that the `RuntimeError` is only triggered if the library was compiled with Python 3.x and the runtime corresponds to a version older than 3.x. The warning even has a typo when thrown in Python 3.10, since it is reported as running Python 3.1.

@molinav I'd be a bit wary of disabling this warning. `CYTHON_LIMITED_API` isn't yet perfect about only using the limited API so you may still run into issues. I think it's a good idea to keep the warning for now (with a long-term ambition to disable it).

> The warning even has a typo when thrown in Python 3.10, since it is reported as running Python 3.1.

I've made a PR to deal with this
